description:
## Why

Currently there isn't a very simple way to implement a `Flash` alert that follows the design specs of the [Alert component](https://design.gitlab.com/components/alert/) in parts of GitLab where a Vue instance doesn't currently exist.

An example of this was found when trying to implement: https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/merge_requests/22933
Resulted in: https://gitlab.com/gitlab-org/gitlab/merge_requests/22933/diffs#37d2cdd5469d664aa921a1680417aa4af9a5fe9e_11_16

**tldr;** A way to fire a more robust Flash message from Ruby without an existing Vue instance isn't currently possible.

## Proposal

By creating a generic `Vue component` that wraps [GlAlert](https://gitlab-org.gitlab.io/gitlab-ui/?path=/story/base-alert--default) we can add a simple way to fire an `up-to-spec` alert with very few lines of code from anywhere in our HAML files.

## How

1. Create a JS entry point in the scoped HAML file: <br />
      ```haml
         - if condition
           #js-vue-alert{ data: { variant: 'tip', message: '...', btn_options: { ... } } }
      ```

2. This entry point will import a small script that inits a Vue instance:
      ```js
        import initVueAlert from '~/vue_alert';
        initVueAlert();
      ```
3. vue-alert will instantiate the Vue instance from `@gitlab/ui`
      ```js
        import { Gl Alert } from '@gitlab/ui';

        export default () => {
          const el = document.querySelector('.js-vue-alert');

          return new Vue({
            el,
            components: { GlAlert },
            ...
          })
        };
      ```

